      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(exec-approval): distinguish non-persistable command from ask=always policy in approval prompt",
        "body": "## Problem\n\nWhen `allowAlwaysPersistence.kind === \"one-shot\"` (e.g. a command that uses shell redirection), `allow-always` is correctly excluded from the allowed decisions. However, the approval prompt showed the same message as when the exclusion is caused by an `ask=always` policy:\n\n> \"The effective approval policy requires approval every time, so Allow Always is unavailable.\"\n\nThis is misleading — the command can be approved, just not saved as a persistent pattern.\n\n## Fix\n\nAdded an optional `nonPersistableCommand` flag to `ExecApprovalPendingReplyParams`. When the caller sets this to `true` (because the command isn't persistable), the prompt shows a distinct message:\n\n> \"Allow Always is unavailable because this command cannot be saved as a reusable pattern (it uses shell redirection or another non-persistable feature).\"\n\nThe `ask=always` path keeps the original wording unchanged.\n\n## Tests\n\nTwo new tests in `exec-approval-reply.test.ts`:\n- `nonPersistableCommand: true` → non-persistable message, no policy message\n- `ask: \"always\"` → policy message, no non-persistable message\n\n```\nTests  34 passed (34)\n```\n\nCloses #97069\n\n🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)",
